624. resupinus: probably in its ordinary sense of ‘lying on his back,’ with the additional notion of ease. But in Homer the Cyclops sprang up to seize the two men, so that some would translate ‘ bending back for a spring.'

‘Nor thoughtless of his own unhappy state.’ 1thacus is not an adjective in agreement with Ulixes, but a noun in apposition to it. It is emphatic; ‘the brain of Ithaca,’ the representative of all wisdom in that island.

perfect to translate the English pluperfect. vinoque sepultus, ‘buried in a drunken sleep.’ The whole phrase, somno vinoque sepultam, occurs Book ii. 265.
